description.value: Deep Egyptian blue 'shabti': in form and details the 'shabti' is traditional with a lappet  wig, clasping a hoe in each hand while a basket is represented pendent in the centre of the back. Incised with text. The eyes and eyebrows were inlaid but only the inlays of the eyes are preserved. They are of white and black opaque glass and, doubtless, the eyelines and eyebrows were also of white glass. This sculpture was moulded and fired.  Preserved broken through knees and assembled.

description.value: Black steatite shabti of Sunero: in this superbly carved funerary figurine the high-ranking military officer, the Master of Horse, Sunero himself is represented. He is not mummiform but is dressed fashionably, sporting a chin beard and wearing a wig with waved strands of hair over the head and ringlets on the shoulders. A two stranded bead necklace and a broad collar overlie his elaborately pleated long linen garment which is completed by a fringed and pleated apron. Most important, Sunero clasps his human-headed 'ba' bird to his chest, and it clings to him with its winged arms. Yet down the front of the apron is the beginning of Chapter 6 of the 'Book of the Dead', the spell to compel the shabti to work for Sunero in the other world. The text continues around the lower half of the figure's back.

description.value: Wooden shabti of Ramses II, reused as an Osiris-figure in the 21st Dynasty. Original detail: a striped nemes-headdress, modelled face, crossed hands holding two hoes, seed-basket on the back, seven rows of Hieroglyphic text down the legs. Secondary decoration includes: crude cutting of the nemes headdress to resemble a tripartite wig, the addition of a tenon at the top of the head for the attachment of an Atef-crown, remains of black pitch and the addition of a long rectangular plinth.
